# Now add the answer sheet with the explanation
from openpyxl.styles import Alignment

# Reload workbook to ensure we have a fresh instance (optional)
wb = load_workbook(output_path)

# Create a new sheet named "Answer" (if it already exists, remove it first)
if "Answer" in wb.sheetnames:
    ws_ans = wb["Answer"]
else:
    ws_ans = wb.create_sheet(title="Answer")

# Explanation text (multi‑line)
explanation = """How to use SUMIFS with criteria from a list or range

1. Basic SUMIFS syntax
   =SUMIFS(sum_range, criteria_range1, criteria1, [criteria_range2, criteria2], …)

2. Date range example
   Suppose dates are in column B (B6:B13) and values to sum are in column D (D6:D13).
   To sum values for the month of the date in cell F5:
   =SUMIFS($D$6:$D$13,
           $B$6:$B$13, ">=" & DATE(YEAR(F5), MONTH(F5), 1),
           $B$6:$B$13, "<=" & EOMONTH(F5, 0))

3. Using a list/range for additional criteria
   If you have a list of allowed categories in G1:G5 and you want to sum only
   rows whose category (in column C) matches any of those, SUMIFS alone cannot
   accept a range of criteria. You have two common options:

   a) SUMPRODUCT (works in both Excel and Google Sheets)
      =SUMPRODUCT(
          ($B$6:$B$13 >= DATE(YEAR(F5), MONTH(F5), 1)) *
          ($B$6:$B$13 <= EOMONTH(F5, 0)) *
          ISNUMBER(MATCH($C$6:$C$13, $G$1:$G$5, 0)) *
          $D$6:$D$13
      )

   b) Helper column with a Boolean test
      In a new column (e.g., column E) put:
          =COUNTIF($G$1:$G$5, C6) > 0
      copy down. Then use SUMIFS with that column:
          =SUMIFS($D$6:$D$13, $B$6:$B$13, ">=" & DATE(YEAR(F5), MONTH(F5), 1),
                            $B$6:$B$13, "<=" & EOMONTH(F5, 0),
                            $E$6:$E$13, TRUE)

4. Google Sheets equivalent
   The same SUMPRODUCT formula works unchanged. Google Sheets also supports
   the ARRAYFORMULA wrapper, e.g.:
   =SUM(FARRAYFORMULA(
        ($B$6:$B$13 >= DATE(YEAR(F5), MONTH(F5), 1)) *
        ($B$6:$B$13 <= EOMONTH(F5, 0)) *
        (COUNTIF($G$1:$G$5, $C$6:$C$13) > 0) *
        $D$6:$D$13
   ))

5. Tips
   • Keep all ranges the same size.
   • Use absolute references ($) for fixed ranges.
   • When using SUMPRODUCT, ensure numeric data; wrap text numbers with VALUE()
     if needed.
   • For large lists, SUMPRODUCT is usually faster than many nested IFs.

This approach guarantees that the SUMIFS (or SUMPRODUCT) respects both the date window
and the dynamic list of criteria you provide."""
"""

# Write the explanation; wrap text for readability
ws_ans["A1"] = explanation
ws_ans["A1"].alignment = Alignment(wrap_text=True)

# Optionally set column width for better display
ws_ans.column_dimensions["A"].width = 100

# Save workbook
wb.save(output_path)
print("Answer sheet added and workbook saved to", output_path)
```
